SIMPLE: posture
RECORDS: 3

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Posture
<hw>Pos"ture</hw> <pr>(?; 135)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[F., fr. L.
<ets>positura</ets>, fr. <ets>ponere</ets>, <ets>positum</ets>, to
place. See <er>Position</er>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>The position of
the body; the situation or disposition of the several parts of the body
with respect to each other, or for a particular purpose; especially
<fld>(Fine Arts)</fld>, the position of a figure with regard to the
several principal members by which action is expressed;
attitude.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Atalanta, the <qex>posture</qex> of whose limbs was so lively
expressed . . . one would have sworn the very picture had run.</q>
<rj><qau>Sir P. Sidney.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>In most strange <qex>postures</qex>⟦br⟧
We have seen him set himself.</q> <rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>The <qex>posture</qex> of a poetic figure is a description of his
heroes in the performance of such or such an action.</q>
<rj><qau>Dryden.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>Place; position; situation.</def>
<mark>[Obs.]</mark> <rj><au>Milton.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>His [man's] noblest <qex>posture</qex> and station in this
world.</q> <rj><qau>Sir M. Hale.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>State or condition, whether of external
circumstances, or of internal feeling and will; disposition; mood;
<as>as, a <ex>posture</ex> of defense; the <ex>posture</ex> of
affairs.</as></def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>The several <qex>postures</qex> of his devout soul.</q>
<rj><qau>Atterbury.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><syn><b>Syn.</b> -- Attitude; position. See
<er>Attitude</er>.</syn>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Posture</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Posture
<hw>Pos"ture</hw> <pr>(?; 135)</pr>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <vmorph>[<pos>imp.
& p. p.</pos> <conjf>Postured</conjf> <pr>(?)</pr>; <pos>p. pr. & vb.
n.</pos> <conjf>Posturing</conjf>.]</vmorph> <def>To place in a
particular position or attitude; to dispose the parts of, with reference
to a particular purpose; <as>as, to <ex>posture</ex> one's self; to
<ex>posture</ex> a model.</as></def> <rj><au>Howell.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Posture</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 3 ====
HEADWORD: Posture
<hw>Pos"ture</hw>, <pos>v. i.</pos> <sn>1.</sn> <def>To assume a
particular posture or attitude; to contort the body into artificial
attitudes, as an acrobat or contortionist; also, to pose.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>Fig.: To assume a character; <as>as, to
<ex>posture</ex> as a saint</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Posturer</ent>⟦br⟧
